sql:
SELECT employment_type_id, employment_type_name
FROM employment_types
WHERE is_part_time = 0 AND is_contractor = 0;

external_knowledge:
- "Full-time employees" refer to those who are not part-time or contractors;
- "Healthy employees" refers to employees with no chronic diseases;
- "Frequent flyer program" is a loyalty program offered by airlines to reward frequent travelers.

- 'Total benefits cost' is the sum of costs of all benefit packages an employee is enrolled in;
- 'Total travel cost' is the sum of all travel expenses recorded for an employee;
- 'Average income by employment type' is the mean annual income of all employees with the same employment type.

- "Good health metrics" refers to an average blood pressure below 120 and an average cholesterol level below 200.;
- "Costly benefit package" refers to a benefit package costing more than $500.;
- "First three levels of the company hierarchy" includes top-level managers and their direct and indirect subordinates up to two levels down.

sql:
SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT ecfp.employee_id) AS frequent_flyer_members_with_chronic_diseases
FROM employee_frequent_flyer_programs ecfp
INNER JOIN employee_chronic_diseases eccd ON ecfp.employee_id = eccd.employee_id;

external_knowledge:
- 'Higher average annual income' refers to employment types with an average annual income greater than $50,000;
- 'Fewer than two chronic conditions' means the employee has less than two chronic diseases;
- 'Elite voyagers of the corporate fleet' is a metaphor for employees with high average income and minimal health issues;
- 'Traversing the seas of business with minimal health anchors' metaphorically describes employees who can focus on their work without significant health-related limitations.

- "Frequent flyers" are employees marked as frequent flyers in the `employees` table;
- "Spread their wings across the globe" refers to employees who have travelled abroad;
- "Most costly journey" is the travel record with the highest cost for each frequent flyer.

- "Large family" refers to having more than 3 family members;
- "Frequent international travel" refers to having more than 2 international travel records;
- "No health issues" refers to having no chronic diseases.
